{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# op-cert: producer signing seam ŌĆö gates mint Ed25519 op-certs with the environment key (expand phase)\n\n## Why\nThe gate producers still sign verdicts with the legacy per-clone HMAC secret via the\n`signing.sign_manifest` seam. The epic's \"Producer-signing & compute-runtime design resolution\"\nsettles fork A ŌĆö **uniform producer signing**: the producers mint `rebar.opcert.v1` DSSE certs\nwith the ambient environment's Ed25519 key, so a local run and a trusted-server run produce the\nsame artifact and there is exactly ONE signature per verdict (no double-signing; the remote\nhandler never signs separately). This story is the expand phase: write-new (Ed25519 op-certs),\nread-both (envelopes + legacy HMAC records).\n\n**Hard dependency (not yet on `main`):** the storage keystone e4df (Gerrit change 660, in review\non the 649ŌåÉ650ŌåÉ660ŌåÉ664 stack) provides `signing.sign_opcert_manifest()` (the envelope-bearing\n`SIGNATURE` event) and `opcert.opcert_from_record()`. Neither exists on current `origin/main` ŌĆö\nthis story MUST NOT start until that stack lands, and its first AC pins a mechanical import\npre-check so the dependency is enforced, not assumed.\n\n## What\n- **The seam is `signing.sign_manifest` itself ŌĆö a global repoint, not per-site edits.**\n  `signing.sign_manifest(ticket_id, manifest, kind=ŌĆ”)` internally mints a `rebar.opcert.v1`\n  DSSE op-cert (via the e4df `sign_opcert_manifest` machinery), deriving bound values when the\n  caller does not supply them: material fingerprint from the canonical manifest (the kind's\n  existing material where present), bound commit from the manifest's `verified-at-sha` line,\n  else current `HEAD`. Every existing caller inherits Ed25519; the full blast radius is\n  enumerated and each site gets a test:\n  - `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py:333` (`sign_plan_review` ŌĆö the plan-review producer);\n  - `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py:538` (`refresh_attestation` ŌĆö the drift-refresh\n    producer; MUST re-sign as an op-cert so a refresh never downgrades a certified op-cert back\n    to an HMAC record in the last-writer-wins attestations map);\n  - `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/resign.py:126` (`resign_plan_review`);\n  - `src/rebar/signing.py:637` (the `rebar sign` CLI);\n  - `src/rebar/_lib_writes.py:638` ŌåÆ `src/rebar/_mcp_writes.py:245` (the MCP `sign_manifest`\n    tool).\n  After this story no caller HMAC-signs these kinds; the contract story (HMAC removal) then\n  deletes the dead HMAC branch.\n- **Environment key genesis** (`src/rebar/signing.py`): on first signing use, auto-generate a\n  **passphrase-free Ed25519 keypair** at `<tracker>/.opcert-key` / `.opcert-key.pub`\n  (`ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -N \"\"`, key file 0600, git-ignored) ŌĆö mirroring the HMAC\n  `.signing-key` genesis it replaces. Genesis is atomic + race-safe with `ssh-keygen`'s two-file\n  reality (`ssh-keygen -f <path>` always writes `<path>` AND `<path>.pub`; it cannot write to\n  an fd): generate into a private `mkdtemp` 0700 staging dir (`ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -N \"\" -f\n  <staging>/key`), then `os.link` the PRIVATE key to `<tracker>/.opcert-key` as the SINGLE\n  exclusive-create commit point (`os.link` fails with `EEXIST` if a concurrent first-signer\n  won; never `os.replace`, which is not exclusive): the loser ADOPTS the winner's key by\n  re-reading the existing file. `.opcert-key.pub` is DERIVATIVE, never a commit point ŌĆö written\n  from the committed private key (`ssh-keygen -y`) and re-derivable any time it is missing.\n  The staging dir is removed in a `finally`. DSSE principal/keyid defaults to the\n  environment's existing `env_id`; `REBAR_OPCERT_ENV_ID` overrides (deployment config).\n  Verify-side key resolution never creates a key.\n- **Key-loss pre-mortem:** a deleted/unreadable key file is regenerated on the next sign (a\n  fresh keypair under the same `env_id`); certs signed by the lost key then read as\n  not-certified on verify and are re-earned on the next gate run ŌĆö the same lifecycle as any\n  stale attestation, no operator ceremony. Only when regeneration itself is impossible\n  (`ssh-keygen` unavailable, tracker directory unwritable) does signing take the degrade path\n  below. (Pinned trusted-environment keys are different:\n  rotation there follows the epic's era protocol in `.rebar/trusted_environments.yaml`.)\n- **Close-gate producer**: the completion-verifier sign call in\n  `src/rebar/_commands/transition_close.py` rides the same repointed seam; the never-sign\n  structural guards (non-PASS, degraded coverage), the material-drift recheck, and the\n  `certifiable: false` / `source==\"local\"` withhold rules are all preserved unchanged.\n- **Read path (expand) ŌĆö the dispatch rule is explicit.** `signing.verify_record` (the single\n  verify chokepoint `verify_signature` and `compute_validity` sit on) dispatches on the RECORD\n  SHAPE. Mechanically, the dispatch lives in a shape-aware wrapper (e.g.\n  `verify_attestation_record(record, ticket_id, *, repo_root)`), because the existing\n  `verify_record(record, ticket_id, key)` takes the raw HMAC secret and cannot carry an op-cert\n  trust root: legacy `signature`-bearing records route to the UNCHANGED\n  `verify_record` + HMAC secret; `envelope`-bearing records route to\n  `attest.registry.verify(OPCERT_KIND, envelope, trust_root)` ŌĆö matching `registry.verify(kind,\n  envelope, trust_root)` ŌĆö under the substrate's OWN kind (the `Policy(SshsigScheme,\n  namespace=OPCERT_NAMESPACE)` entry `opcert.register_opcert_policy()` registers;\n  `OPCERT_KIND = OPCERT_NAMESPACE = \"rebar.opcert.v1\"`, the constants in `attest/opcert.py`,\n  giving domain separation from `rebar.authorship.v1`), with `trust_root` built from the\n  environment's own public key via `authorship.allowed_signers_from_keys([own_pub],\n  principal)`. EVERY `verify_record` caller moves to the wrapper ŌĆö the complete inventory (grep-verified):\n  `signing.verify_signature` (signing.py:675), `signing.verify_attestations` (signing.py:692 ŌĆö\n  the all-kinds iterator), and `_engine_support/validate.py:117` (`signature_findings`). The\n  wrapper's translation rule for envelope records is a LITERAL table (downstream readers see\n  the existing contract unchanged; `key_id` carries the record's `principal`, which keeps\n  `drift_refresh_candidate`'s provenance read ŌĆö `llm/plan_review/attest.py:529`,\n  `result.get(\"key_id\")` ŌĆö working as-is):\n  - `record.principal != own env_id` ŌåÆ the WRAPPER returns `verdict: \"foreign_key\"`,\n    `certified: false` WITHOUT invoking the scheme (there is no key to verify with ŌĆö exactly\n    today's HMAC `foreign_key` semantics; `SshsigScheme` itself never emits `foreign_key`);\n  - `record.principal == own env_id` ŌåÆ `registry.verify(OPCERT_KIND, envelope, root)` and the\n    `Verdict` maps `verified ŌåÆ certified`, `verdict ŌåÆ verdict` (pass-through), `reason ŌåÆ\n    reason`. The strings this path can emit, verbatim from the code: `\"certified\"`,\n    `\"mismatch\"`, `\"invalid\"` (malformed principal/namespace), `\"unavailable\"` (ssh-keygen\n    missing ŌĆö `sshsig.py:110`), plus the registry's defensive `\"unknown_kind\"` /\n    `\"unknown_scheme\"`. (`\"key_not_valid_at_era\"` is emitted only by the merge-gate era path,\n    `opcert.verify_opcert`, and is already in the schema enum.) The attestation kind's\n  legacy POLICY pins are NOT touched: `POLICY[\"plan-review\"]` / `POLICY[\"completion-verifier\"]`\n  remain HMAC-pinned through the expand phase and are removed by the contract story (8f1d). The\n  envelope is verified against the environment's own public key\n  (`.opcert-key.pub`) for same-environment verification ŌĆö a cert whose `principal` is another\n  environment is classified `foreign_key` BY THE WRAPPER per the translation table below (the\n  scheme is never invoked for it); a record carrying\n  the legacy `signature` (HMAC hex) field routes to the unchanged HMAC path (removed later by\n  the contract story). The event/record plumbing is the e4df dependency's CONTRACT ŌĆö consumed here, not\n  re-built, and asserted BEHAVIORALLY at story start by the dependency-gate AC (rather than\n  taken on faith): the envelope-bearing `SIGNATURE` event, the reducer passthrough of\n  `envelope`/`principal`/bound fields into `attestations[kind]`, and `opcert_from_record`\n  read-back. The envelope-bearing record RETAINS the `manifest` list exactly as the\n  legacy record carries it (envelope and manifest coexist on the e4df record), so\n  `compute_validity`'s manifest-derived checks (`manifest_deps` / `manifest_material` /\n  `manifest_regver` / `signing.verified_at_sha_from_manifest`) read it unchanged.\n  Validity-on-read lifecycle rules (reopen, code drift,\n  material drift) apply to envelope attestations identically. Worked example of the shape:\n  `attestations[\"plan-review\"]` holds `{algorithm: \"sshsig\", envelope: \"<encoded DSSE>\",\n  material_fingerprint: \"<hex>\", merged_log_commit: \"<sha>\", principal: \"<env_id>\"}` (no HMAC\n  hex), where `merged_log_commit` is the commit the gate verified against ŌĆö the manifest's\n  `verified-at-sha` line (the seam's bound-commit derivation above; the e4df event already\n  carries the field) ŌĆö and `verify_signature(ticket, kind=\"plan-review\")` returns its existing\n  result shape with `certified: true` and the op-cert verdict string (`certified`) ŌĆö the exact\n  field contract is pinned by the existing `verify_signature_result.schema.json`.\n- **Downstream `signature`-field consumers are enumerated and updated** (they would otherwise\n  break or mis-report on envelope records):\n  - `src/rebar/signing.py:648` ŌĆö the `rebar sign` text-mode report hardcodes\n    `record['signature'][:16]`; updated to render the envelope digest + principal for op-cert\n    records (no `KeyError`);\n  - `src/rebar/_engine_support/validate.py` `signature_findings()` ŌĆö checks\n    `record.get('signature')` and would report envelope-bearing records as `unsigned`; updated\n    to route through the same `verify_record` shape dispatch.\n- **Output-schema contract** (`docs/output-schemas.md` seam): `sign_result.schema.json` ŌĆö and\n  the `SignResultOut` Pydantic model that the MCP `sign_manifest` tool validates against\n  (`src/rebar/_mcp_writes.py:245`) and that `rebar sign --output json` conforms to ŌĆö currently\n  REQUIRES a `signature` (HMAC hex) field; the op-cert record carries `envelope` instead. `verify_signature_result.schema.json`'s CLOSED `verdict` enum (currently `[\"unsigned\",\n  \"foreign_key\", \"certified\", \"mismatch\", \"key_not_valid_at_era\"]`) is widened with EXACTLY the\n  four strings the op-cert dispatch path can newly emit ŌĆö `\"invalid\"`, `\"unavailable\"`\n  (`SshsigScheme.verify`, sshsig.py:110/125), `\"unknown_kind\"`, `\"unknown_scheme\"`\n  (`registry.verify`, registry.py:100/107); `certified`/`mismatch`/`key_not_valid_at_era` are\n  already present ŌĆö a backward-compatible enum extension, with the schema-drift test\n  regenerated. The sign-result\n  shape is updated in ALL THREE of its artifacts together: `sign_result.schema.json`,\n  `_mcp_models.py::SignResultOut` (`signature` required ŌåÆ optional alongside `envelope`), and\n  the `types.py::SignResult` TypedDict (lines 215-224; `signature: str` becomes\n  `NotRequired`). Expand-phase, the schema admits BOTH result shapes (the legacy HMAC shape\n  and the envelope shape `{algorithm: \"sshsig\", envelope, principal, material_fingerprint,\n  merged_log_commit, ŌĆ”}` with `signature` no longer required); the contract story (8f1d) later\n  tightens it to envelope-only.\n- **Degrade, never wedge**: if `ssh-keygen` (OpenSSH Ōēź 8.9, `sshsig.ensure_available()`) is\n  unavailable or the key is unreadable and cannot be regenerated, signing records the existing\n  in-band `{signed: false, error: ŌĆ”}` outcome; no local operation is blocked by signing itself.\n  A project whose claim/close gate requires the signature then blocks at that gate with a clear\n  install-OpenSSH remediation message.\n\n## Scope\n- In: the global `sign_manifest` seam repoint + the five enumerated call sites; key genesis +\n  principal resolution; expand-phase read path; the `sign_result.schema.json` / `SignResultOut`\n  contract update; tests below.\n- Out: HMAC removal (the contract story, 8f1d); the remote service and its client command\n  (ee0b); AWS IaC (the deploy story); any change to gate YAMLs or verdict schemas.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Dependency gate (behavioral): on the branch this story builds on (the e4df stack has\n      landed), the import check `python -c \"from rebar.signing import sign_opcert_manifest; from rebar.attest.opcert import opcert_from_record\"`\n      succeeds AND a round-trip passes ŌĆö `sign_opcert_manifest` on a fixture ticket yields a\n      reduced state whose `attestations[kind]` carries `envelope`/`principal`/bound fields and\n      `opcert_from_record` returns the envelope; recorded as the story's first verification\n      step (this asserts e4df's reducer/event contract instead of claiming it).\n- [ ] First signing use in a fresh environment generates `<tracker>/.opcert-key`(+`.pub`),\n      passphrase-free Ed25519, mode 0600, git-ignored, via the body's exclusive-create mechanism (0700 staging dir, `os.link` of\n      the private key as the sole commit point, derivative `.pub` ŌĆö never `os.replace`); a test\n      asserts genesis, permissions, exclusive-create under a concurrent first-sign race (exactly\n      one keypair survives; the loser adopts it ŌĆö no overwrite), and that verify-side resolution\n      never creates a key.\n- [ ] A passing plan review produces an envelope-bearing `SIGNATURE` event (no HMAC hex) whose\n      DSSE subject binds `{ticket_id, material_fingerprint, verified-at sha, kind=\"plan-review\"}`;\n      a test asserts `verify_signature(kind=\"plan-review\")` certifies it in the same environment\n      and that the never-sign guards (non-PASS / degraded coverage) still refuse to sign.\n- [ ] Drift-refresh and resign re-sign as op-certs: tests drive `refresh_attestation` and\n      `resign_plan_review` and assert the resulting record still carries a DSSE envelope (a\n      refresh never downgrades an op-cert to an HMAC record).\n- [ ] The MCP `sign_manifest` tool and the `rebar sign` CLI emit envelope-bearing events via the\n      same seam; a test drives each end-to-end and asserts the DSSE envelope is present.\n- [ ] A gated close produces an envelope-bearing `SIGNATURE` event (kind `completion-verifier`)\n      via the same seam; a test asserts the material-drift recheck still withholds signing on\n      drift and `certifiable: false` still closes unsigned.\n- [ ] Expand-phase read-both: a test asserts a legacy HMAC attestation written before this change\n      still verifies/reads as today, alongside a new envelope attestation on the same ticket\n      (kind-keyed coexistence per the additive attestations model).\n- [ ] `REBAR_OPCERT_ENV_ID` overrides the DSSE principal; absent, the principal equals the\n      environment's `env_id`; a test asserts both.\n- [ ] With `ssh-keygen` unavailable (patched `ensure_available`), or the key file unreadable\n      AND regeneration impossible (unwritable tracker dir), a\n      plan-review PASS records the in-band `{signed: false, ŌĆ”}` outcome and the operation exits\n      successfully; a test asserts the claim gate then reports the missing-attestation block\n      with a remediation that names OpenSSH Ōēź 8.9.\n- [ ] `sign_result.schema.json` and `SignResultOut` admit the envelope-bearing result shape\n      (and, expand-phase, still admit the legacy HMAC shape); a test validates a real op-cert\n      sign result against the schema, and the MCP `sign_manifest` tool returns it without\n      validation error.\n- [ ] Read-path dispatch: a test asserts the shape-aware wrapper (`verify_attestation_record`)\n      routes an envelope-bearing record to the op-cert verifier and a `signature`-bearing record\n      to the unchanged `verify_record` HMAC path, on the same store.\n- [ ] Consumer regressions: tests assert `rebar sign` text-mode output renders an op-cert\n      record without error, and `_engine_support/validate.py` `signature_findings()` does not\n      report a certified envelope-bearing record as unsigned.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784022886754201001,"uuid":"81ec8afd-1cd2-438f-9919-9c8d191449da"}